"I don't want to go on TV.

246
00:09:56,430 --> 00:09:58,223
I want to go on field trips."

247
00:09:58,307 --> 00:10:00,058
That was the decision I made.

248
00:10:00,142 --> 00:10:01,143
THE POPULARITY WAS TOO MUCH FOR HER
AT A YOUNG AGE

249
00:10:01,810 --> 00:10:03,770
Music is what made you famous

250
00:10:03,854 --> 00:10:05,981
and what made you uncomfortable.

251
00:10:06,481 --> 00:10:07,900
But music was also your relief.

252
00:10:08,275 --> 00:10:10,194
- <i>Pansori </i>was your relief.
- That's right.

253
00:10:10,277 --> 00:10:11,612
Yes.

254
00:10:11,695 --> 00:10:13,071
FROM YE-SOL TO <i>PANSORI</i>

255
00:10:13,155 --> 00:10:14,698
How did you start?

256
00:10:15,324 --> 00:10:16,950
- Ye-sol...
- Yes.

257
00:10:17,242 --> 00:10:20,871
once went on a TV show
where she had to learn <i>pansori</i>.

258
00:10:20,954 --> 00:10:24,666
<i>It was a children's show on MBC</i>
<i>called Hey! It's Sunday.</i>

259
00:10:24,750 --> 00:10:25,709
<i>- I see.</i>
<i>- Yes.</i>

260
00:10:25,792 --> 00:10:27,544
How old were you at the time?

261
00:10:27,628 --> 00:10:29,254
- I was ten.
- I see.

262
00:10:29,630 --> 00:10:34,092
A man was sitting in the dressing room
with a <i>buk,</i> a type of drum.

263
00:10:34,176 --> 00:10:37,638
Out of nowhere, he told me to do <i>pansori</i>
and hit the <i>buk</i>.

264
00:10:38,180 --> 00:10:40,724
He went, "Why get upset..."

265
00:10:40,807 --> 00:10:42,518
I was a kid,

266
00:10:42,601 --> 00:10:46,021
suddenly hearing this adult
sing <i>pansori</i> at me.

267
00:10:47,314 --> 00:10:48,941
And it sounded so ugly.

268
00:10:49,566 --> 00:10:53,654
It was such a rough sound
that I was unfamiliar with.

269
00:10:53,737 --> 00:10:55,822
To a ten-year-old's ears,

270
00:10:55,906 --> 00:10:57,908
- it can sound ugly.
- Right.

271
00:10:58,742 --> 00:11:01,703
Apparently,
I kept my mouth shut for an hour.

272
00:11:02,329 --> 00:11:03,163
I didn't want to do it.

273
00:11:05,415 --> 00:11:08,502
- Even though the master told you to?
- Yes.

274
00:11:08,585 --> 00:11:10,963
- Because you thought it sounded ugly.
- Yes.

275
00:11:11,046 --> 00:11:14,508
I was used to singing
"Ye-sol" in a pretty voice.

276
00:11:14,591 --> 00:11:16,969
But I was asked to make
such an ugly sound.

277
00:11:17,052 --> 00:11:18,512
I hated that.

278
00:11:18,595 --> 00:11:21,473
In my days of hosting <i>Star King</i>,

279
00:11:21,557 --> 00:11:23,058
we used this formula a lot.

280
00:11:23,141 --> 00:11:25,018
The master of one field

281
00:11:25,102 --> 00:11:26,854
- and a child prodigy.
- Right.

282
00:11:26,937 --> 00:11:29,231
There's a kind of magic
in that combination.

283
00:11:29,314 --> 00:11:31,525
The one who introduced <i>pansori</i>

284
00:11:31,608 --> 00:11:32,818
to Ye-sol, or young Ja-ram,

285
00:11:32,901 --> 00:11:35,070
- must have been someone special.
- Yes.

286
00:11:35,612 --> 00:11:38,824
It was the late Eun Hee-jin.

287
00:11:38,907 --> 00:11:40,450
<i>CHUNHYANGGA</i> BY EUN HEE-JIN

288
00:11:40,534 --> 00:11:43,829
At the time, he played
the leading role in anything

289
00:11:43,912 --> 00:11:46,415
by the National <i>Changgeuk</i>
Company of Korea.

290
00:11:46,498 --> 00:11:48,417
He was the best male<i> pansori </i>master.

291
00:11:48,500 --> 00:11:51,295
You met him when you were ten.
You hated the sound.

292
00:11:51,670 --> 00:11:53,755
Yes, but it was fascinating.

293
00:11:55,382 --> 00:11:56,633
It was cool.

294
00:11:56,967 --> 00:12:00,053
This charismatic person
in front of me was going, "Go on, try.

295
00:12:00,679 --> 00:12:01,847
You'll like it once you do."

296
00:12:02,222 --> 00:12:03,307
"Why get upset..."

297
00:12:03,390 --> 00:12:04,850
"That's it!" Like that.

298
00:12:05,309 --> 00:12:06,977
He coaxed me

299
00:12:07,060 --> 00:12:09,229
into doing <i>pansori</i>.

300
00:12:09,313 --> 00:12:10,981
It was the compliments...

301
00:12:11,398 --> 00:12:12,399
- Carrot and stick.
- Right.

302
00:12:12,482 --> 00:12:13,775
I think

303
00:12:14,067 --> 00:12:16,069
that for him,

304
00:12:16,153 --> 00:12:19,031
he had to make that kid do it
so that the day would be over.

305
00:12:19,573 --> 00:12:21,200
"There you go. You're doing a good job."

306
00:12:21,283 --> 00:12:23,493
GOING HOME IS IMPORTANT,
EVEN TO A GREAT MASTER LIKE HIM

307
00:12:24,119 --> 00:12:25,913
- It was important
- Right.

308
00:12:25,996 --> 00:12:28,165
- for them to get the footage.
- Exactly.

309
00:12:28,248 --> 00:12:29,750
- So he could go home.
- Yes.

310
00:12:30,751 --> 00:12:32,753
Everyone had a job to do.

311
00:12:33,295 --> 00:12:35,464
- You definitely threw the master off.
- Right.

312
00:12:35,547 --> 00:12:38,884
He kept soothing and coaxing me

313
00:12:38,967 --> 00:12:40,844
until I finally opened my mouth.

314
00:12:40,928 --> 00:12:42,971
I guess he liked what he heard.

315
00:12:43,055 --> 00:12:45,974
He told my parents, "She has potential.

316
00:12:47,142 --> 00:12:48,936
I don't have a protégé yet.

317
00:12:49,895 --> 00:12:51,021
Would she like to be?"

318
00:12:51,104 --> 00:12:53,315
After hearing just a little bit?

319
00:12:53,732 --> 00:12:55,651
- You only sang children's songs before.
- I did.

320
00:12:55,734 --> 00:12:57,903
What amazes and shocks me is this.

321
00:12:57,986 --> 00:13:00,864
<i>Your voice must've been</i>
<i>bright and clear at the time.</i>

322
00:13:00,948 --> 00:13:03,408
<i>How did he recognize your talent?</i>

323
00:13:03,951 --> 00:13:06,411
The basics of <i>pansori</i>,
teaching by word and heart,

324
00:13:06,495 --> 00:13:08,288
start with imitating.

325
00:13:08,372 --> 00:13:10,874
You're supposed to
imitate your teacher exactly

326
00:13:11,208 --> 00:13:12,709
and copy them quickly.

327
00:13:13,794 --> 00:13:16,129
So when he sang,

328
00:13:16,505 --> 00:13:19,299
and I copied his tone and rhythm closely,

329
00:13:19,383 --> 00:13:21,134
like a machine,

330
00:13:21,218 --> 00:13:24,763
I think that's when he thought,
"She has talent."

331
00:13:24,847 --> 00:13:27,599
Imitation is the best skill

332
00:13:27,683 --> 00:13:29,309
that <i>pansori</i> singers have.

333
00:13:29,893 --> 00:13:31,436
I don't know about other sports,

334
00:13:31,520 --> 00:13:32,688
but it's the same for <i>ssireum</i>,
Korean wrestling.

335
00:13:32,771 --> 00:13:36,108
You can't do sports
without the ability to watch and copy.

336
00:13:36,191 --> 00:13:38,652
The most important skill is
being able to copy.

337
00:13:38,735 --> 00:13:40,112
It must be a gift.

338
00:13:40,195 --> 00:13:43,699
Watching, imitating, and doing the same.

339
00:13:43,782 --> 00:13:46,159
- Making a technique yours.
- Yes.

340
00:13:46,326 --> 00:13:47,244
Making it yours.

341
00:13:47,327 --> 00:13:50,080
It seems like there are similarities

342
00:13:50,163 --> 00:13:52,666
in these different fields. Right?

343
00:13:52,749 --> 00:13:53,917
It's fascinating.

344
00:13:54,001 --> 00:13:56,086
- It's the same for sports and art.
- Right.

345
00:13:57,671 --> 00:13:59,923
When I was in middle school,

346
00:14:00,382 --> 00:14:02,634
I tried <i>ssireum</i> for the first time,

347
00:14:03,552 --> 00:14:05,053
and it was exhausting.

348
00:14:05,137 --> 00:14:06,722
When you hold on to the <i>satba</i>, the belt,

349
00:14:06,805 --> 00:14:09,266
you get blisters on your hands.

350
00:14:09,349 --> 00:14:10,392
- I'd guess so.
- Yes.

351
00:14:10,475 --> 00:14:12,477
And that hurts your hands.

352
00:14:13,061 --> 00:14:15,230
So I thought it wasn't my path.

353
00:14:15,647 --> 00:14:17,107
It was too hard.

354
00:14:17,191 --> 00:14:19,151
But then, my coach came to my house

355
00:14:19,234 --> 00:14:21,320
and persuaded me without giving up.

356
00:14:21,778 --> 00:14:23,363
He knew I'd be good at it.

357
00:14:23,447 --> 00:14:25,407
I asked him how, and he said

358
00:14:25,490 --> 00:14:27,159
that he saw me at home

359
00:14:27,242 --> 00:14:30,287
eating five bowls of rice
despite being sad

360
00:14:30,370 --> 00:14:31,622
and weeping.

361
00:14:32,247 --> 00:14:33,874
HOCRATES IN MIDDLE SCHOOL

362
00:14:33,957 --> 00:14:36,585
I was crying, "I don't want to do it,"
while eating.

363
00:14:37,127 --> 00:14:38,378
He saw me eat and thought,

364
00:14:38,462 --> 00:14:40,130
"He's going to make it big."

365
00:14:40,589 --> 00:14:43,592
HE DID MAKE IT BIG,
BOTH LITERALLY AND FIGURATIVELY

366
00:14:43,675 --> 00:14:45,093
Anyway, I digress.

367
00:14:45,177 --> 00:14:47,221
Sorry for telling that silly story.

368
00:14:47,304 --> 00:14:48,597
TIME TO GET BACK ON TOPIC

369
00:14:48,680 --> 00:14:51,266
He never had a protégé up to that point.

370
00:14:51,350 --> 00:14:54,019
He said that it would
negatively impact his skills.

371
00:14:54,102 --> 00:14:56,605
"It's not easy taking in a protégé.

372
00:14:56,980 --> 00:14:58,232
It'll affect your skills."

373
00:14:58,649 --> 00:15:00,609
- That's what he always said.
- I see.

374
00:15:00,817 --> 00:15:05,197
But he took me in as his first protégé

375
00:15:05,280 --> 00:15:09,117
and taught me with care and affection.

376
00:15:10,577 --> 00:15:13,789
HER <i>PANSORI</i> MENTOR
WHO TAUGHT HER WITH CARE AND AFFECTION

377
00:15:15,040 --> 00:15:18,043
EUN HEE-JIN
LIVING HUMAN TREASURE-LEVEL ARTIST

378
00:15:21,880 --> 00:15:26,009
LEE JA-RAM (YE-SOL)
GUGAK NATIONAL HIGH SCHOOL

379
00:15:26,552 --> 00:15:29,721
THE "YE-SOL" LABEL STILL FOLLOWED HER
EVEN IN HIGH SCHOOL

380
00:15:31,557 --> 00:15:34,434
When you first heard <i>pansori</i>
at ten years old,

381
00:15:34,518 --> 00:15:36,311
the sound felt ugly,

382
00:15:36,395 --> 00:15:37,688
like it was all crumpled.

383
00:15:37,771 --> 00:15:40,023
- Yes.
- But you had to make that sound.

384
00:15:40,107 --> 00:15:41,775
- Right.
- So how did you practice?

385
00:15:41,859 --> 00:15:43,819
My teacher always said,

386
00:15:43,902 --> 00:15:47,155
"The other pansori protégés
sing inside the closet."

387
00:15:47,531 --> 00:15:50,075
He said that so many times,
it's etched in my mind.

388
00:15:50,617 --> 00:15:52,286
The reason why they did that

389
00:15:52,369 --> 00:15:54,204
was that they were too loud.

390
00:15:54,288 --> 00:15:56,248
- The neighbors would say something
- Right.

391
00:15:56,331 --> 00:15:57,624
and complain.

392
00:15:57,708 --> 00:16:00,335
So it meant I had to be
in the soundproof closet

393
00:16:00,419 --> 00:16:02,838
<i>and practice hard in there.</i>

394
00:16:03,505 --> 00:16:04,882
Because it's a small space,

395
00:16:04,965 --> 00:16:07,134
- the sound would echo.
- Yes.

396
00:16:08,177 --> 00:16:11,638
I go into the walk-in closet to practice.

397
00:16:12,014 --> 00:16:15,142
This is what I do
the moment I open the door.

398
00:16:15,684 --> 00:16:16,935
I would put in my earplugs.

399
00:16:17,019 --> 00:16:21,982
<i>Let it be</i>
<i>All worldly things are futile.</i>

400
00:16:22,065 --> 00:16:23,025
That's how I would start.

401
00:16:23,108 --> 00:16:24,568
ANOTHER FEATURE OF THE CLOSET
This is a short warm-up song.

402
00:16:25,319 --> 00:16:27,946
There are clothes hanging in the closet.

403
00:16:28,030 --> 00:16:29,656
When I'm in a good mood,

404
00:16:29,740 --> 00:16:32,159
a green coat would start looking
like an audience member.

405
00:16:32,242 --> 00:16:34,953
The clothes all start looking like people.

406
00:16:35,579 --> 00:16:38,707
Then I think,
"Okay, let me tell you a story today."

407
00:16:38,790 --> 00:16:40,250
I get in that mood.

408
00:16:40,334 --> 00:16:43,670
I suddenly realize why
a <i>pansori</i> singer from Joseon wrote that.

409
00:16:43,921 --> 00:16:44,755
I really do.

410
00:16:45,672 --> 00:16:48,759
- For example, I'll sing an ornamentation.
- Okay.

411
00:16:49,801 --> 00:16:52,012
<i>Lady Gwi-deok</i>

412
00:16:52,095 --> 00:16:53,847
Let's say that's an ornamentation.

413
00:16:54,556 --> 00:16:57,559
LADY GWI-DEOK: A CHARACTER IN <i>SIMCHEONGGA</i>
It's supposed to go like, "Lady Gwi-deok."

414
00:16:57,643 --> 00:16:58,894
The notes go like that.

415
00:16:59,394 --> 00:17:03,232
I don't know why it was written that way
when I'm learning it.

416
00:17:03,315 --> 00:17:04,858
I'm just imitating.

417
00:17:05,609 --> 00:17:09,029
But on a good day of practice,
I start to see the full picture.

418
00:17:09,780 --> 00:17:13,534
I see Blind Man Sim calling out,
"Lady Gwi-deok."

419
00:17:13,617 --> 00:17:17,120
I see the<i> pansori </i>singer from Joseon

420
00:17:17,204 --> 00:17:19,039
thinking about how to sing it.

421
00:17:19,122 --> 00:17:20,958
I can feel the songwriter's intention.

422
00:17:21,041 --> 00:17:24,294
"That's how the combination of notes
came to be."

423
00:17:24,795 --> 00:17:29,132
"Then should I vocalize the sound
from further back?"

424
00:17:29,216 --> 00:17:32,135
If I used to sing it without depth,

425
00:17:32,219 --> 00:17:35,430
I would now try to add
depth and thickness.

426
00:17:35,514 --> 00:17:37,850
I make these discoveries.

427
00:17:37,933 --> 00:17:40,310
When I'm feeling good,

428
00:17:40,394 --> 00:17:44,147
it's like I feel a link
to the Joseon dynasty.

429
00:17:45,274 --> 00:17:46,984
It's rare, but it happens.

430
00:17:47,734 --> 00:17:48,944
Not often though.

431
00:17:49,027 --> 00:17:50,988
When you're at your best,

432
00:17:51,071 --> 00:17:52,906
you get linked to the Joseon dynasty?

433
00:17:52,990 --> 00:17:55,617
My imagination starts to fly.

434
00:17:57,035 --> 00:17:59,496
"That's why the<i> pansori</i> singers
wrote this song

435
00:17:59,580 --> 00:18:01,039
and these words.

436
00:18:01,123 --> 00:18:02,958
That's crazy. It's amazing."

437
00:18:03,041 --> 00:18:05,252
I'm in awe.

438
00:18:05,878 --> 00:18:08,088
There isn't any sheet music
for <i>pansori,</i> right?

439
00:18:08,630 --> 00:18:09,464
There isn't.

440
00:18:09,548 --> 00:18:12,634
Since the Joseon dynasty,
people have used personal signs.

441
00:18:12,718 --> 00:18:14,136
SYMBOLS MARKING HOW IT SHOULD SOUND
They're symbols.

442
00:18:14,219 --> 00:18:15,846
I brought them to show you.

443
00:18:16,680 --> 00:18:18,015
This is traditional <i>pansori</i>.

444
00:18:18,098 --> 00:18:20,184
- Yes.
- It's <i>Sugungga</i>.

445
00:18:21,977 --> 00:18:23,228
Is this the sheet music?

446
00:18:23,312 --> 00:18:24,521
This is how it looks.

447
00:18:24,605 --> 00:18:26,273
Can you read it?

448
00:18:26,982 --> 00:18:28,650
Is this the sheet music?

449
00:18:29,693 --> 00:18:31,361
This is wild.

450
00:18:31,445 --> 00:18:33,655
They're like codes.

451
00:18:34,114 --> 00:18:36,158
They're like secret codes.

452
00:18:36,241 --> 00:18:37,367
Only I can read them.

453
00:18:37,451 --> 00:18:41,038
Did the master teach you everything?

454
00:18:41,121 --> 00:18:42,998
He'd say, "Mark them."

455
00:18:43,457 --> 00:18:44,875
"Draw an 'O' for <i>hap</i>,

456
00:18:45,209 --> 00:18:46,585
and 'X' for <i>gak."</i>

457
00:18:46,919 --> 00:18:49,046
He told me the names of rhythmic patterns.

458
00:18:49,129 --> 00:18:50,881
I still use those signs.

459
00:18:50,964 --> 00:18:52,299
"O" for <i>hap</i>,

460
00:18:52,591 --> 00:18:53,926
"X" for <i>gak</i>.

461
00:18:54,968 --> 00:18:56,595
I have no idea how to read this.

462
00:18:56,720 --> 00:18:59,973
"If I write a letter to my wife on a pot,

463
00:19:00,057 --> 00:19:02,142
she will find and send my liver...

464
00:19:02,226 --> 00:19:03,352
Do so."

465
00:19:04,186 --> 00:19:05,270
Let's not include that scene.

466
00:19:06,480 --> 00:19:07,356
So that's what it's like.

467
00:19:07,731 --> 00:19:10,317
Follow this with your eyes.

468
00:19:10,400 --> 00:19:11,610
Okay, where?

469
00:19:11,693 --> 00:19:14,029
- From where the tiger comes down.
- Here?

470
00:19:14,112 --> 00:19:17,407
A lot of Korean people
know "Tiger is Coming"

471
00:19:17,491 --> 00:19:19,535
- by that one song.
- Yes.

472
00:19:20,035 --> 00:19:21,286
This is the original.

473
00:19:21,370 --> 00:19:23,539
<i>A tiger is coming down</i>

474
00:19:23,622 --> 00:19:25,499
<i>A tiger is coming down</i>

475
00:19:25,582 --> 00:19:29,753
<i>A beast is coming down</i>
<i>A deep valley of pine trees</i>

476
00:19:29,837 --> 00:19:32,130
<i>It's shaking its head</i>

477
00:19:32,214 --> 00:19:34,132
<i>Its two ears are ripped</i>

478
00:19:34,216 --> 00:19:36,260
<i>Its body is mottled</i>

479
00:19:36,343 --> 00:19:40,597
<i>Its tail is more than a foot long</i>

480
00:19:40,681 --> 00:19:42,182
It starts like that.

481
00:19:42,891 --> 00:19:46,937
This is combined
with different instruments

482
00:19:47,020 --> 00:19:48,272
in that song.

483
00:19:49,106 --> 00:19:52,192
<i>Pansori</i> is an art of imagination.

484
00:19:53,235 --> 00:19:57,990
Depending on how well
I've trained my imagination,

485
00:19:58,073 --> 00:20:00,617
I can use my imagination better on stage.

486
00:20:00,909 --> 00:20:02,995
And when I use my imagination better,

487
00:20:03,078 --> 00:20:05,372
that helps the audience
use their imagination.

488
00:20:05,873 --> 00:20:08,083
They're like, "Oh, no! Blind Man Sim!"

489
00:20:08,166 --> 00:20:11,503
It's an art form that you enjoy
using your own imagination.

490
00:20:11,587 --> 00:20:15,132
Everyone's imagination
comes together in that moment.

491
00:20:15,632 --> 00:20:17,676
It's such an intriguing art form.

492
00:20:17,926 --> 00:20:20,846
So someone who's seen
a <i>pansori</i> performance once

493
00:20:21,305 --> 00:20:23,849
usually keeps going to see more.

494
00:20:23,932 --> 00:20:25,267
Because it's exciting.

495
00:20:26,351 --> 00:20:28,020
You feel a sort of camaraderie.

496
00:20:29,521 --> 00:20:32,232
"HOW DO TWO PEOPLE PERFORM FOR TWO HOURS

497
00:20:32,316 --> 00:20:34,318
ON A STAGE WITH NO STAGE SET

498
00:20:34,401 --> 00:20:36,612
OTHER THAN A LITTLE FLOOR MAT?"

499
00:20:37,196 --> 00:20:39,364
BEFORE THEY KNOW IT,
THE PEOPLE WHO SAID THAT

500
00:20:39,448 --> 00:20:42,910
START LAUGHING, SIGHING, AND BRINGING
AN IMAGINATION TO LIFE TOGETHER

501
00:20:42,993 --> 00:20:44,077
I LOVE THOSE MOMENTS

502
00:20:44,161 --> 00:20:46,413
FROM <i>TODAY'S JARAM</i>

503
00:20:46,914 --> 00:20:48,582
After that process,

504
00:20:48,665 --> 00:20:50,334
you accomplished something big.

505
00:20:50,417 --> 00:20:52,252
When you were 20 years old,

506
00:20:52,336 --> 00:20:54,796
you performed <i>Chunhyangga</i> in full
in eight hours.

507
00:20:55,464 --> 00:21:01,220
IN 1999, SHE PERFORMED
<i>CHUNHYANGGA</i> IN FULL IN EIGHT HOURS

508
00:21:01,845 --> 00:21:05,724
THE MOMENT IT CAME TO AN END,

509
00:21:05,807 --> 00:21:08,143
SHE WAS OVERCOME WITH TEARS

510
00:21:08,936 --> 00:21:11,313
<i>That was amazing. She did it.</i>

511
00:21:11,396 --> 00:21:13,649
YOUNGEST PERSON TO ACHIEVE THE GUINNESS
WORLD RECORD FOR LONGEST SINGING MARATHON

512
00:21:13,732 --> 00:21:15,108
<i>After she finished the performance...</i>

513
00:21:15,192 --> 00:21:17,152
Wow, I was truly

514
00:21:17,236 --> 00:21:18,111
sick and tired.

515
00:21:19,696 --> 00:21:22,908
You led the audience on your own
for eight hours

516
00:21:23,116 --> 00:21:24,701
together on that journey.

517
00:21:24,785 --> 00:21:26,578
- It was just me on stage.
- Yes.

518
00:21:26,787 --> 00:21:29,331
The <i>buk</i> player took turns.

519
00:21:30,332 --> 00:21:31,375
If they didn't,

520
00:21:31,458 --> 00:21:33,377
their backs would give out.

521
00:21:33,460 --> 00:21:36,922
I took two 20-minute breaks in between.

522
00:21:37,297 --> 00:21:39,049
During those breaks,

523
00:21:39,675 --> 00:21:41,385
I went and ate glutinous rice.

524
00:21:41,468 --> 00:21:45,222
People in the audience
also ate the food that was prepared there

525
00:21:45,681 --> 00:21:47,599
before coming back to their seats.

526
00:21:47,683 --> 00:21:48,767
Yes.

527
00:21:48,851 --> 00:21:51,687
It was like undertaking
a feat of strength.

528
00:21:52,563 --> 00:21:56,024
It was a shared experience.

529
00:21:56,108 --> 00:21:58,652
- It was an epic journey.
- Yes.

530
00:21:58,735 --> 00:22:00,404
After those eight hours,

531
00:22:00,487 --> 00:22:01,989
you suffered

532
00:22:02,072 --> 00:22:03,740
- Yes.
- from "singer's pain"?

533
00:22:03,824 --> 00:22:06,368
There's this thing called "singer's pain."

534
00:22:06,451 --> 00:22:08,453
I didn't know when I was younger.

535
00:22:08,912 --> 00:22:13,083
I suffered greatly from it
after the eight-hour performance.

536
00:22:13,166 --> 00:22:15,669
Do all <i>pansori</i> singers know this?

537
00:22:16,170 --> 00:22:18,463
Anyone who's performed one in full
would know.

538
00:22:18,547 --> 00:22:20,674
- It's something you have to go through.
- Right.

539
00:22:21,091 --> 00:22:25,053
First, when you have it, your body hurts.

540
00:22:25,721 --> 00:22:26,805
It just hurts.

541
00:22:27,181 --> 00:22:29,099
You're in so much pain.

542
00:22:29,558 --> 00:22:32,603
Also, I was always dozing off on the bus.

543
00:22:32,686 --> 00:22:34,730
I was like that for a whole year.

544
00:22:35,147 --> 00:22:37,316
Simply put, I lost a lot of stamina.

545
00:22:37,774 --> 00:22:39,693
I went to a Korean medicine clinic.

546
00:22:39,776 --> 00:22:41,653
I was 23 years old, but they said

547
00:22:41,778 --> 00:22:45,365
I had the body of a woman in her thirties
who neglected postpartum care.

548
00:22:45,449 --> 00:22:48,243
That was how low my energy was.

549
00:22:48,327 --> 00:22:49,995
That whole situation

550
00:22:50,495 --> 00:22:51,747
was a big problem

551
00:22:51,830 --> 00:22:53,207
in your parents' eyes.

552
00:22:53,290 --> 00:22:54,333
It was a huge problem.

553
00:22:54,416 --> 00:22:55,626
You were low on energy.

554
00:22:55,709 --> 00:22:56,919
I had no energy at all.

555
00:22:57,002 --> 00:22:58,504
- Exactly.
- My mother

556
00:22:58,879 --> 00:23:01,089
tried cooking every animal for me.

557
00:23:01,548 --> 00:23:02,549
I'm serious.

558
00:23:03,884 --> 00:23:05,844
Animal rights have improved now,

559
00:23:05,928 --> 00:23:07,221
so I feel bad saying it.

560
00:23:07,304 --> 00:23:09,348
But she's cooked a black goat,

561
00:23:09,848 --> 00:23:11,141
and a northern snakehead.

562
00:23:11,558 --> 00:23:14,102
Why does it have to be cooked alive?

563
00:23:14,186 --> 00:23:17,648
I don't know why,
but she took a strong and live one

564
00:23:18,190 --> 00:23:20,859
and pushed it down in a pot at home.

565
00:23:20,943 --> 00:23:22,861
It was moving around because of the heat,

566
00:23:22,945 --> 00:23:25,364
but my mom pushed it down
with her strength.

567
00:23:25,447 --> 00:23:28,575
You take the grease that comes out of it,

568
00:23:28,659 --> 00:23:30,118
add other things in there,

569
00:23:30,202 --> 00:23:31,745
and simmer to make medicine.

570
00:23:31,828 --> 00:23:33,288
Is a live one more effective?

571
00:23:33,372 --> 00:23:34,581
Apparently.

572
00:23:34,665 --> 00:23:36,458
Have you ever tried it?

573
00:23:37,209 --> 00:23:39,169
It's absolutely revolting.

574
00:23:39,878 --> 00:23:40,712
It's inedible.

575
00:23:40,796 --> 00:23:42,798
- It tastes disgusting.
- Yes.

576
00:23:42,881 --> 00:23:45,801
But at some point,
I started to feel better.

577
00:23:45,884 --> 00:23:47,469
- My goodness.
- It's all thanks to my mom.

578
00:23:47,553 --> 00:23:48,846
- And her devotion.
- Yes.

579
00:23:48,929 --> 00:23:50,305
We don't know which nutrients helped.

580
00:23:50,389 --> 00:23:52,057
Right, I don't know what it was,

581
00:23:52,140 --> 00:23:54,184
but I eventually bounced back.

582
00:23:54,268 --> 00:23:57,020
I read there was
something you did with bamboo.

583
00:23:57,104 --> 00:23:58,981
That would be poop water.
Would you like to hear about it?

584
00:23:59,064 --> 00:24:00,107
Is it true?

585
00:24:01,316 --> 00:24:02,776
- Is it based on facts?
- Wait.

586
00:24:02,860 --> 00:24:05,487
There are some things

587
00:24:05,571 --> 00:24:09,575
that many people have heard about <i>pansori</i>.

588
00:24:09,658 --> 00:24:11,493
You need to drink poop water
to get the right sound

589
00:24:11,577 --> 00:24:13,036
and train under a waterfall.

590
00:24:13,120 --> 00:24:14,413
Those are the big two.

591
00:24:14,496 --> 00:24:15,664
Trying to shout

592
00:24:15,747 --> 00:24:17,457
- louder than the waterfall?
- Yes.

593
00:24:17,541 --> 00:24:18,834
- You had to be louder.
- Right.

594
00:24:18,917 --> 00:24:20,878
- First, the poop water.
- Yes.

595
00:24:21,378 --> 00:24:22,462
It's half true.

596
00:24:23,589 --> 00:24:25,424
But not in the present day.

597
00:24:25,799 --> 00:24:28,635
<i>Pansori</i> singers in the Joseon dynasty
were so poor

598
00:24:28,719 --> 00:24:30,846
that they couldn't even eat properly.

599
00:24:30,929 --> 00:24:32,306
When they had singer's pain,

600
00:24:32,389 --> 00:24:33,473
it was harder for them.

601
00:24:33,557 --> 00:24:34,850
They couldn't afford medicine.

602
00:24:34,933 --> 00:24:37,644
- They couldn't get nutrients.
- They couldn't get any.

603
00:24:38,103 --> 00:24:40,939
In old-style outhouses,

604
00:24:41,190 --> 00:24:43,775
they'd stick bamboo in the middle of it.

605
00:24:43,859 --> 00:24:45,485
Then, in between the nodes,

606
00:24:45,569 --> 00:24:46,945
clear water pooled.

607
00:24:47,029 --> 00:24:47,863
It's poop water.

608
00:24:47,946 --> 00:24:50,282
- It came from human feces.
- Yes.

609
00:24:50,365 --> 00:24:51,950
When they drank that water

610
00:24:52,034 --> 00:24:54,828
and sweat a lot in their sleep overnight,

611
00:24:54,912 --> 00:24:56,205
it's believed the toxins would leave,

612
00:24:56,288 --> 00:24:59,917
and all the nutrients from the feces
would stay in the body.

613
00:25:00,000 --> 00:25:02,377
That's why <i>pansori </i>singers from Joseon

614
00:25:02,461 --> 00:25:04,379
drank poop water.

615
00:25:04,463 --> 00:25:05,672
There's no need for that now.

616
00:25:05,756 --> 00:25:07,508
We have great vitamin supplements.

617
00:25:08,509 --> 00:25:09,384
That's true.

618
00:25:10,469 --> 00:25:11,929
And a lot of great food.

619
00:25:12,012 --> 00:25:13,764
You couldn't get vitamin supplements then.

620
00:25:13,847 --> 00:25:16,266
That's why they drank poop water instead.

621
00:25:16,350 --> 00:25:18,227
You really can't do that now.

622
00:25:18,310 --> 00:25:21,688
Of course not! You'd die
from the endocrine disruptors.

623
00:25:22,689 --> 00:25:24,191
- Don't try this.
- Never.

624
00:25:24,274 --> 00:25:26,902
- The endocrine disruptors...
- You'd die.

625
00:25:26,985 --> 00:25:29,279
It was only possible
in the Joseon dynasty.

626
00:25:29,696 --> 00:25:34,117
It was only possible
because everything they ate was natural.

627
00:25:34,201 --> 00:25:36,787
And another stereotype
is the waterfall thing.

628
00:25:37,204 --> 00:25:40,082
That's also half true and half false.

629
00:25:40,290 --> 00:25:41,917
The reason people went to train
in the mountains

630
00:25:42,000 --> 00:25:45,420
is that not everyone
is born with a powerful voice.

631
00:25:45,796 --> 00:25:48,048
BORN WITH A POWERFUL VOICE
Someone who's born small like me

632
00:25:48,757 --> 00:25:51,343
has to train a lot
to control their volume.

633
00:25:51,426 --> 00:25:54,429
If you learn how to make it louder,
you can make it softer.

634
00:25:54,805 --> 00:25:57,057
So you go to the mountains
to make it louder.

635
00:25:57,850 --> 00:26:00,310
Under a waterfall,
you can't hear yourself.

636
00:26:00,394 --> 00:26:01,603
The sound drowns everything out.

637
00:26:01,687 --> 00:26:05,399
So if you try to be louder
so you can hear yourself,

638
00:26:05,482 --> 00:26:09,027
your muscles start working with you.

639
00:26:09,111 --> 00:26:10,737
They go up there to train that.

640
00:26:10,821 --> 00:26:12,865
Even streams can cover your sound.

641
00:26:12,948 --> 00:26:13,949
- The sound.
- Right.

642
00:26:14,032 --> 00:26:16,493
- Waterfalls can be really loud.
- Yes.

643
00:26:16,577 --> 00:26:19,121
That's why they train there.

644
00:26:19,204 --> 00:26:20,038
I see.

645
00:26:20,664 --> 00:26:22,875
I CHALLENGED MYSELF

646
00:26:22,958 --> 00:26:25,252
TO PERFORM IT IN FULL IN EIGHT HOURS

647
00:26:25,335 --> 00:26:28,130
TO TEST MY OWN ABILITIES AND WILLPOWER

648
00:26:28,213 --> 00:26:30,257
IF I HAD TO DO IT AGAIN, I DON'T KNOW

649
00:26:30,340 --> 00:26:32,301
IF THERE WERE 1,000 PEOPLE

650
00:26:32,384 --> 00:26:34,678
IN THEIR TWENTIES TO THIRTIES
IN THE AUDIENCE,

651
00:26:34,761 --> 00:26:36,346
I COULD DO IT

652
00:26:36,430 --> 00:26:39,183
FROM HER INTERVIEW WITH <i>THE JOONGANG</i>
IN 2002

653
00:26:39,600 --> 00:26:41,310
"She changes the game.

654
00:26:42,269 --> 00:26:43,812
Lee Ja-ram becomes a genre."

655
00:26:45,439 --> 00:26:46,440
That's so cool.

656
00:26:47,441 --> 00:26:48,483
Lee Ja-ram becomes a genre.

657
00:26:50,444 --> 00:26:52,613
There are many people

658
00:26:52,696 --> 00:26:54,156
who are good at <i>pansori</i>.

659
00:26:54,239 --> 00:26:55,407
- There are.
- Yes.

660
00:26:55,824 --> 00:26:58,035
But the reason why you're special

661
00:26:58,118 --> 00:26:59,995
- is because you created new <i>pansori.</i>
- Right.

662
00:27:00,078 --> 00:27:01,663
You created

663
00:27:01,747 --> 00:27:03,165
- a new traditional vocal piece.
- That's right.

664
00:27:03,248 --> 00:27:06,210
Someone reviewers had this to say.

665
00:27:06,293 --> 00:27:08,045
"Through Ja-ram's voice,

666
00:27:08,128 --> 00:27:13,050
it's like the late writers
are coming back to life."

667
00:27:13,300 --> 00:27:15,135
- I love that.
- Yes.

668
00:27:15,219 --> 00:27:17,095
- What a nice comment, right?
- Right.

669
00:27:17,471 --> 00:27:20,015
You made many people come alive
through <i>pansori.</i>

670
00:27:20,098 --> 00:27:22,392
Could you tell me about this?

671
00:27:23,227 --> 00:27:26,396
<i>The Good Person of Szechwan</i>
by Bertolt Brecht

672
00:27:26,480 --> 00:27:28,815
- was made into <i>Sacheonga</i>.
- Right.

673
00:27:28,899 --> 00:27:30,776
<i>The Old Man and the Sea</i> by Hemingway

674
00:27:30,859 --> 00:27:32,986
was made into a <i>pansori</i>
with the same name.

675
00:27:33,070 --> 00:27:35,155
Most recently,

676
00:27:35,239 --> 00:27:36,990
Leo Tolstoy's

677
00:27:37,074 --> 00:27:40,619
short story, <i>Master and Man</i>,

678
00:27:40,911 --> 00:27:43,247
was made into a <i>pansori</i>
called <i>Snow, Snow, Snow</i>.

679
00:27:43,330 --> 00:27:46,375
Was there something that prompted you
to create these adaptations?

680
00:27:46,667 --> 00:27:47,626
Yes.

681
00:27:49,878 --> 00:27:51,129
I had this thirst.

682
00:27:51,713 --> 00:27:55,175
When I was in middle school
and high school,

683
00:27:55,259 --> 00:27:59,179
<i>I loved listening to bands like Nirvana,</i>
<i>Pearl Jam, and so on.</i>

684
00:27:59,263 --> 00:28:01,431
When I go to concerts or plays that I like

685
00:28:01,515 --> 00:28:03,392
and I see their stage sets,

686
00:28:04,184 --> 00:28:06,186
they use spectacular lights

687
00:28:06,270 --> 00:28:08,605
and cool stage equipment

688
00:28:08,689 --> 00:28:10,440
and have big audiences.

689
00:28:10,524 --> 00:28:12,150
I wanted that too.

690
00:28:12,901 --> 00:28:14,444
I wanted to do that too.

691
00:28:14,778 --> 00:28:17,698
I thought, "Why is<i> pansori </i>so fixed?"

692
00:28:18,115 --> 00:28:20,492
"Couldn't <i>pansori </i>use different lighting?"

693
00:28:20,742 --> 00:28:24,413
"Couldn't<i> pansori</i> talk
about more familiar subject matters?"

694
00:28:24,788 --> 00:28:26,915
I think I started
questioning these things.

695
00:28:27,374 --> 00:28:32,296
That led me to jump into
creating <i>pansori </i>performances.

696
00:28:33,463 --> 00:28:35,424
- That's very honest.
- Yes.

697
00:28:35,507 --> 00:28:37,509
- You were honestly frustrated.
- Yes.

698
00:28:37,593 --> 00:28:41,138
So what was the first piece you created?

699
00:28:42,181 --> 00:28:45,726
The first piece I created
as an individual creator was <i>Sacheonga</i>.

700
00:28:46,685 --> 00:28:50,105
I took <i>The Good Person of Szechwan</i>
by dramatist Bertolt Brecht

701
00:28:50,189 --> 00:28:53,192
and brought it
to the Korean city of Sacheon.

702
00:28:53,275 --> 00:28:55,319
That was <i>Sacheonga</i>.

703
00:28:55,402 --> 00:28:58,530
That piece was a big hit.

704
00:28:58,614 --> 00:29:02,492
It got a sensational reaction
in the performing arts scene.

705
00:29:02,576 --> 00:29:06,663
It spread by word of mouth over the years.

706
00:29:06,747 --> 00:29:09,416
No other <i>pansori </i>performance
has done this,

707
00:29:09,499 --> 00:29:13,837
but it even had a month-long run.

708
00:29:14,296 --> 00:29:16,256
It didn't just stop there.

709
00:29:16,340 --> 00:29:18,509
Didn't it also gain popularity abroad?

710
00:29:18,592 --> 00:29:22,304
There's a Polish festival called
International Theatre Festival Kontakt.

711
00:29:22,387 --> 00:29:24,806
It's a prestigious theater festival.

712
00:29:24,890 --> 00:29:27,142
Starting with the performance in Poland,

713
00:29:27,226 --> 00:29:29,228
we did a tour around Europe.

714
00:29:29,311 --> 00:29:33,065
Then we went to New York,
Chicago, and so on.

715
00:29:34,024 --> 00:29:37,778
THE PIECE SHE CREATED
GAINED POPULARITY OVERSEAS AS WELL

716
00:29:37,861 --> 00:29:39,321
TICKET OFFICE
<i>UKCHUKGA, THE TALE OF MOTHER COURAGE</i>

717
00:29:39,404 --> 00:29:42,032
SOLD OUT IN MANY DIFFERENT COUNTRIES,

718
00:29:42,115 --> 00:29:45,827
SUCH AS POLAND, FRANCE,
UK, ROMANIA, USA, ETC

719
00:29:46,745 --> 00:29:50,666
Hearing you talk about it
is giving me goosebumps.

720
00:29:51,458 --> 00:29:53,418
Was there a particularly memorable show?

721
00:29:53,919 --> 00:29:55,128
There were so many.

722
00:29:55,629 --> 00:29:57,589
While performing <i>Sacheonga</i>,

723
00:29:58,006 --> 00:30:01,093
there was a moment
during a show in Chicago.

724
00:30:01,426 --> 00:30:04,096
Here's the plot of <i>Sacheonga</i>.

725
00:30:04,179 --> 00:30:06,557
There's a kind woman named Sun-deok,

726
00:30:06,640 --> 00:30:07,808
and she's large.

727
00:30:08,475 --> 00:30:12,563
Large women are
somewhat mocked in society.

728
00:30:12,646 --> 00:30:14,606
In order to overcome difficulties,

729
00:30:14,690 --> 00:30:17,150
Sun-deok puts on a suit

730
00:30:17,234 --> 00:30:19,236
and pretends to be a man
called Nam Jae-su.

731
00:30:19,319 --> 00:30:21,738
And suddenly, everything is possible.

732
00:30:21,822 --> 00:30:24,616
That's what the story is about.

733
00:30:25,075 --> 00:30:27,411
SUN-DEOK DRESSES AS A MAN TO SURVIVE

734
00:30:27,494 --> 00:30:29,955
AND STARTS ANOTHER LIFE AS NAM JAE-SU

735
00:30:30,038 --> 00:30:32,624
PROBLEMS THAT WEREN'T TAKEN SERIOUSLY
AS A WOMAN

736
00:30:32,708 --> 00:30:35,127
NATURALLY START TO BE SETTLED AS A MAN

737
00:30:35,210 --> 00:30:37,796
BUT HER INNER CONFLICT DEEPENS

738
00:30:37,880 --> 00:30:40,716
AS SHE CONTINUES TO LIVE LIFE
AS SOMEONE SHE'S NOT

739
00:30:40,799 --> 00:30:43,802
THIS PIECE ASKS
THROUGH THE CHARACTER SUN-DEOK

740
00:30:43,886 --> 00:30:47,472
IF ONE CAN SURVIVE BEING A GOOD PERSON
AND BEING THEMSELVES

741
00:30:47,556 --> 00:30:49,558
In the middle of the performance,

742
00:30:49,641 --> 00:30:52,144
a large woman suddenly stood up.

743
00:30:52,936 --> 00:30:55,606
TEARFUL STANDING OVATION

744
00:30:55,689 --> 00:30:58,108
- A standing ovation?
- In the middle of the show.

745
00:30:58,192 --> 00:31:01,361
So I was like, "Thank you."

746
00:31:01,778 --> 00:31:04,072
And kept performing. But in that moment,

747
00:31:04,489 --> 00:31:05,866
I got goosebumps.

748
00:31:06,158 --> 00:31:08,785
It was a moment where the story met

749
00:31:09,661 --> 00:31:11,330
that person's life.

750
00:31:12,289 --> 00:31:13,957
I think that's what artists seek

751
00:31:14,041 --> 00:31:15,959
when they perform on stage.

752
00:31:16,335 --> 00:31:20,380
To meet the history of the people
who are there for the art.

753
00:31:20,964 --> 00:31:22,549
To find that common ground,

754
00:31:23,008 --> 00:31:25,093
artists keep searching.

755
00:31:25,177 --> 00:31:27,095
And I met that moment.

756
00:31:27,429 --> 00:31:28,680
I met that person's life.

757
00:31:28,931 --> 00:31:31,517
That made me extremely happy.

758
00:31:33,227 --> 00:31:36,188
I TOLD THEM TO BELIEVE THE POWER

759
00:31:36,271 --> 00:31:39,691
MY LANGUAGE WILL HAVE ON THE WORLD

760
00:31:39,775 --> 00:31:41,777
I GOT UP ON STAGE, SANG,

761
00:31:41,860 --> 00:31:45,113
TOLD STORIES, DECLARED, AND SATIRIZED,

762
00:31:45,197 --> 00:31:48,992
FEELING AS IF I WAS ACCOMPLISHING
SOMETHING GREAT

763
00:31:49,076 --> 00:31:51,620
FROM <i>TODAY'S JARAM</i>

764
00:31:51,703 --> 00:31:53,705
But an important question I have

765
00:31:53,789 --> 00:31:57,125
is that language-wise,
it's in a foreign language to them.

766
00:31:57,209 --> 00:31:58,168
That's right.

767
00:31:58,252 --> 00:32:00,504
- No matter how hard they study,
- Yes.

768
00:32:00,587 --> 00:32:03,507
- there must be limitations to subtitles.
- Right.

769
00:32:03,590 --> 00:32:07,261
But they're still moved.
They shed tears and relate to it.

770
00:32:07,344 --> 00:32:09,304
What do you think
is the secret behind that?

771
00:32:10,138 --> 00:32:12,057
- I also find it amazing.
- Yes.

772
00:32:12,683 --> 00:32:14,935
The subtitles play a very important role.

773
00:32:15,018 --> 00:32:18,272
Foreigners want to know
what I'm trying to say

774
00:32:18,355 --> 00:32:20,440
with these songs.

775
00:32:20,524 --> 00:32:22,651
The subtitles are above my head on stage.

776
00:32:22,734 --> 00:32:23,694
It's up there?

777
00:32:23,777 --> 00:32:24,987
- Above my head.
- Okay.

778
00:32:25,070 --> 00:32:28,407
So in the beginning,
everyone is like this.

779
00:32:28,782 --> 00:32:30,033
They're reading the subtitles.

780
00:32:30,534 --> 00:32:32,160
But when I'm talking about something,

781
00:32:32,828 --> 00:32:33,829
they're like, "Huh?"

782
00:32:35,372 --> 00:32:38,500
Their eyes start staying longer on me.

783
00:32:39,126 --> 00:32:40,961
At first, they focus on subtitles,

784
00:32:41,044 --> 00:32:42,921
but the focus moves on to me.

785
00:32:43,005 --> 00:32:44,882
Then, they start to think,

786
00:32:45,424 --> 00:32:47,551
"Wait! This is about me!"

787
00:32:47,634 --> 00:32:49,178
They reach that point.

788
00:32:49,553 --> 00:32:51,597
That's the power of <i>pansori</i>.

789
00:32:51,680 --> 00:32:53,724
There's a sense that we're all together

790
00:32:53,807 --> 00:32:55,893
in the same space at the same time.

791
00:32:55,976 --> 00:32:59,521
I think it's also because
my pieces are contemporary.

792
00:32:59,980 --> 00:33:03,400
I think I pick a story
to make into a <i>pansori</i>

793
00:33:03,483 --> 00:33:07,321
when the characters
have something in common with me.

794
00:33:07,404 --> 00:33:10,073
In my most recent piece,

795
00:33:10,157 --> 00:33:12,409
there's Santiago
from <i>The Old Man and the Sea</i>.

796
00:33:12,826 --> 00:33:15,120
I see that fisherman

797
00:33:15,662 --> 00:33:17,080
as a <i>pansori</i> singer.

798
00:33:17,915 --> 00:33:22,002
He fights a marlin
for three days straight. He fights nature.

799
00:33:22,544 --> 00:33:24,463
"Who am I, and who are you?

800
00:33:25,047 --> 00:33:26,757
I've been a fisherman for years."

801
00:33:26,840 --> 00:33:30,344
All of his thoughts and words

802
00:33:31,220 --> 00:33:35,849
made me think of
the life of a <i>pansori </i>singer.

803
00:33:35,933 --> 00:33:38,727
Actually, at our bookshop...

804
00:33:38,810 --> 00:33:39,645
GLANCING

805
00:33:39,728 --> 00:33:41,313
...there's not just me.

806
00:33:41,897 --> 00:33:44,107
- There's the real owner of this shop.
- Really?

807
00:33:44,191 --> 00:33:46,276
The owner might ask
to see a scene from it.

808
00:33:46,360 --> 00:33:48,695
- From <i>The Old Man and the Sea?</i>
- Yes, it may be requested.

809
00:33:48,779 --> 00:33:50,280
- I see. I can do that.
- Yes.

810
00:33:50,364 --> 00:33:51,490
- What?
- Sure, I can.

811
00:33:51,573 --> 00:33:52,991
You don't have to.

812
00:33:53,075 --> 00:33:55,244
I'll explain it to the owner. It's okay.

813
00:33:55,327 --> 00:33:56,870
But I want to.

814
00:33:57,579 --> 00:33:59,414
WE'LL GLADLY ACCEPT IT
Then you can.

815
00:34:01,667 --> 00:34:03,168
Which part?

816
00:34:04,002 --> 00:34:06,129
It's this part.

817
00:34:06,213 --> 00:34:08,173
The old man is holding on to the marlin,

818
00:34:08,257 --> 00:34:10,467
when it jumps out of the water once.

819
00:34:11,218 --> 00:34:12,553
Then it dives back in.

820
00:34:13,554 --> 00:34:16,557
The old man has been at it
for two days now.

821
00:34:17,391 --> 00:34:19,685
He's exhausted,
and just as the fish jumps out,

822
00:34:19,768 --> 00:34:21,228
this is what he thinks.

823
00:34:21,937 --> 00:34:24,898
"He is two feet longer than the skiff,"

824
00:34:24,982 --> 00:34:26,233
the old man said.

825
00:34:26,483 --> 00:34:28,277
The line was going out fast

826
00:34:28,360 --> 00:34:32,614
but steadily
and the fish was not panicked.

827
00:34:33,323 --> 00:34:35,367
The old man was trying with both hands

828
00:34:35,450 --> 00:34:37,995
to keep the line
just inside of breaking strength.

829
00:34:38,662 --> 00:34:42,499
He is a great fish
and I must convince him, he thought.

830
00:34:42,791 --> 00:34:46,295
If I were him
I would put in everything now and go

831
00:34:46,378 --> 00:34:47,754
until something broke.

832
00:34:47,838 --> 00:34:49,381
But, thank God,

833
00:34:49,506 --> 00:34:50,924
they are not as intelligent

834
00:34:51,008 --> 00:34:53,594
as we who kill them;

835
00:34:53,677 --> 00:34:55,846
although they are

836
00:34:55,929 --> 00:34:58,724
more noble and more able.

837
00:34:59,892 --> 00:35:01,310
It's this part.

838
00:35:01,393 --> 00:35:03,645
This is how I adapted it in the script.

839
00:35:04,897 --> 00:35:08,400
HODONG'S BOOKSHOP

840
00:35:09,985 --> 00:35:13,947
Santiago had many thoughts in that moment.

841
00:35:15,365 --> 00:35:18,202
He probably doesn't know
what he was thinking either.

842
00:35:20,412 --> 00:35:24,917
<i>Was that a fish I saw?</i>

843
00:35:26,752 --> 00:35:28,420
<i>It's a marlin</i>

844
00:35:29,129 --> 00:35:32,549
<i>A huge marlin</i>

845
00:35:34,218 --> 00:35:38,889
<i>I didn't mean to run into such a big one</i>

846
00:35:40,891 --> 00:35:44,561
<i>Why did it suddenly jump out?</i>

847
00:35:44,645 --> 00:35:47,606
<i>Did something startle it?</i>

848
00:35:47,689 --> 00:35:50,108
<i>Did it jump out to see me?</i>

849
00:35:51,985 --> 00:35:55,113
<i>It jumped out</i>

850
00:35:55,197 --> 00:35:59,117
<i>So I could see it</i>

851
00:36:00,160 --> 00:36:02,746
<i>To intimidate me</i>

852
00:36:02,829 --> 00:36:05,290
<i>So it can escape</i>

853
00:36:09,419 --> 00:36:13,465
<i>What a noble and magnificent creature</i>

854
00:36:13,882 --> 00:36:16,510
<i>That makes me</i>

855
00:36:16,593 --> 00:36:19,638
<i>Desperate to catch you</i>

856
00:36:19,721 --> 00:36:22,599
<i>You're the one I've been waiting for</i>

857
00:36:22,683 --> 00:36:25,269
<i>The last 85 days</i>

858
00:36:26,103 --> 00:36:31,191
<i>I'm feeling weak all of a sudden</i>

859
00:36:31,275 --> 00:36:34,069
<i>But if I don't say anything,</i>

860
00:36:34,152 --> 00:36:36,905
<i>No one will know</i>

861
00:36:37,865 --> 00:36:42,828
<i>My shoulders suddenly feel heavier now</i>

862
00:36:42,911 --> 00:36:45,581
<i>But if I keep my mouth shut</i>

863
00:36:45,664 --> 00:36:48,166
<i>No one will know</i>

864
00:36:48,250 --> 00:36:50,210
<i>Nice to see you</i>

865
00:36:50,460 --> 00:36:53,964
<i>Marlin</i>

866
00:36:54,047 --> 00:36:55,757
<i>Bring it on</i>

867
00:36:56,216 --> 00:36:59,303
<i>Marlin</i>

868
00:37:00,053 --> 00:37:01,346
That's my version.

869
00:37:01,430 --> 00:37:03,599
Brilliant! Bravo!

870
00:37:05,684 --> 00:37:07,561
You cheered "Bravo!"

871
00:37:07,644 --> 00:37:10,063
because you're Hocrates.

872
00:37:10,147 --> 00:37:12,024
<i>Pansori</i> surely is

873
00:37:12,107 --> 00:37:13,650
- a form of total art.
- Yes.

874
00:37:13,734 --> 00:37:16,820
- You tell a story with oral literature.
- Yes.

875
00:37:16,904 --> 00:37:18,113
- It really feels that way.
- It does.

876
00:37:18,197 --> 00:37:20,949
- You said I was telling a story.
- Yes.

877
00:37:21,033 --> 00:37:23,869
That's the magma of <i>pansori</i>, so to speak.

878
00:37:23,952 --> 00:37:26,914
The will to tell a story

879
00:37:26,997 --> 00:37:29,541
gives me the strength to vocalize.

880
00:37:30,000 --> 00:37:33,128
- Of course, <i>Reset</i> is important, but...
- Yes.

881
00:37:34,505 --> 00:37:35,380
Ta-da!

882
00:37:37,508 --> 00:37:39,885
<i>TODAY'S JARAM</i> BY LEE JA-RAM
I loved it.

883
00:37:39,968 --> 00:37:42,429
- You wrote a book.
- Yes.

884
00:37:42,513 --> 00:37:45,849
I was wondering
what kind of person you were,

885
00:37:45,933 --> 00:37:47,476
so I read the whole book.

886
00:37:47,559 --> 00:37:49,811
- Thank you.
- Every single word.

887
00:37:49,895 --> 00:37:51,647
You wrote to your audience that,

888
00:37:51,730 --> 00:37:55,776
as a<i> pansori </i>singer,

889
00:37:56,026 --> 00:37:59,321
you will leave a mark somehow.

890
00:37:59,404 --> 00:38:01,365
So you emphasized--

891
00:38:01,448 --> 00:38:03,492
- "Come see me."
- While you're alive,

892
00:38:03,700 --> 00:38:06,495
they should come see you
so they can say they did.

893
00:38:06,578 --> 00:38:07,496
- Yes.
- Right?

894
00:38:08,038 --> 00:38:11,208
How confident do you have to be?

895
00:38:11,291 --> 00:38:13,669
How sure about your art do you have to be

896
00:38:13,752 --> 00:38:16,380
to promote yourself like that
to the readers?

897
00:38:18,090 --> 00:38:19,800
I just gave it a shot.

898
00:38:23,095 --> 00:38:24,596
They'll at least come see me.

899
00:38:26,598 --> 00:38:28,350
You're very honest.

900
00:38:28,934 --> 00:38:30,686
Also, to keep my word

901
00:38:30,853 --> 00:38:34,189
to the people who read that and came,
I would try harder.

902
00:38:34,648 --> 00:38:35,899
That's why I wrote it.

903
00:38:35,983 --> 00:38:38,610
So that the future me won't be lazy.

904
00:38:39,152 --> 00:38:41,655
Here's the thing about <i>pansori </i>as a genre.

905
00:38:42,072 --> 00:38:43,991
It's not easy for an average person

906
00:38:44,074 --> 00:38:46,201
to think about going to see
a stage performance.

907
00:38:46,285 --> 00:38:48,370
And when they're choosing what to see,

908
00:38:48,453 --> 00:38:50,330
because Koreans love music,

909
00:38:50,414 --> 00:38:51,999
they would be enthusiastic about
going to see a musical.

910
00:38:52,082 --> 00:38:54,168
They might consider
watching a play or a dance.

911
00:38:55,210 --> 00:38:57,629
But they rarely pick
traditional Korean music first.

912
00:38:58,463 --> 00:39:01,925
So, <i>pansori</i> is never the priority

913
00:39:02,009 --> 00:39:03,760
in that choice.

914
00:39:04,261 --> 00:39:09,016
So to me, them coming to see me perform
was the most important part.

915
00:39:09,099 --> 00:39:12,144
I think that's why I wrote such a thing.

916
00:39:12,227 --> 00:39:16,190
So they can come and judge for themselves.

917
00:39:17,357 --> 00:39:18,984
Sitting against the boat's edge

918
00:39:20,027 --> 00:39:21,987
in pitch-black darkness,

919
00:39:23,071 --> 00:39:26,658
he looks around his surroundings.

920
00:39:29,536 --> 00:39:32,289
I WANT TO MAKE THE AUDIENCE EXPERIENCE

921
00:39:32,372 --> 00:39:35,876
THE SIDES OF <i>PANSORI</i>
THAT I THINK ARE BEAUTIFUL

922
00:39:35,959 --> 00:39:39,129
AND ENJOY THE MOMENT
WHEN THE PERFORMANCE OCCURS

923
00:39:39,213 --> 00:39:42,007
I REMEMBER THE DAYS
WHEN THE CROWD'S REACTION

924
00:39:42,090 --> 00:39:44,009
TOOK ME TO A BETTER PLACE

925
00:39:44,092 --> 00:39:45,761
FROM <i>TODAY'S JARAM</i>

926
00:39:53,852 --> 00:39:56,396
<i>It rises</i>

927
00:39:56,939 --> 00:40:00,234
<i>It rises up</i>

928
00:40:00,317 --> 00:40:03,529
<i>Breaking the surface of the water</i>

929
00:40:04,196 --> 00:40:06,532
We've come to the last question.

930
00:40:06,615 --> 00:40:08,742
You've shown us so many sides today.

931
00:40:08,992 --> 00:40:10,160
- Yes.
- If you look at <i>Reset</i>,

932
00:40:10,244 --> 00:40:12,246
Earth is reset by humanity's mistakes

933
00:40:12,329 --> 00:40:14,623
and it begins anew.

934
00:40:14,706 --> 00:40:18,085
Who do you want to be remembered as
in the distant future?

935
00:40:20,921 --> 00:40:22,130
I...

936
00:40:22,756 --> 00:40:26,510
actually don't want to be remembered
by too many people.

937
00:40:28,387 --> 00:40:30,889
I hope my works will stay alive
and be remembered

938
00:40:31,473 --> 00:40:34,142
more than myself.

939
00:40:34,726 --> 00:40:37,437
Just like traditional <i>pansori</i>
that survived 400 years,

940
00:40:37,521 --> 00:40:39,815
I hope after 100 years,

941
00:40:39,898 --> 00:40:43,861
my works will be alive
as the <i>pansori</i> of this generation.

942
00:40:43,944 --> 00:40:45,571
They will be.

943
00:40:45,654 --> 00:40:48,323
Through you, Hemingway came back to life.

944
00:40:49,157 --> 00:40:50,158
So will you.

945
00:40:50,242 --> 00:40:51,326
I hope so.

946
00:40:53,453 --> 00:40:55,372
The cutest neighborhood in the world is?

947
00:40:55,455 --> 00:40:56,540
- Kangho-dong!
- Yes.

948
00:40:56,623 --> 00:40:58,667
<i>Hodong's Bookshop</i> in Kangho-dong.

949
00:40:59,293 --> 00:41:01,295
Today's book, <i>Take My Voice</i>.

950
00:41:01,670 --> 00:41:02,880
The price for this...

951
00:41:03,463 --> 00:41:04,381
I got it.

952
00:41:05,465 --> 00:41:07,968
The price for today's book

953
00:41:08,051 --> 00:41:10,721
is <i>The Martian</i>, <i>Artemis</i>,

954
00:41:10,929 --> 00:41:12,806
and <i>Project Hail Mary!</i>

955
00:41:14,349 --> 00:41:16,852
The space trilogy by Andy Weir.

956
00:41:17,311 --> 00:41:18,687
Let me tell you about them.

957
00:41:18,770 --> 00:41:20,439
You spread the beauty of sound

958
00:41:20,522 --> 00:41:23,317
beyond languages and borders, Ja-ram.

959
00:41:23,400 --> 00:41:25,986
Now, may that sound spread beyond earth

960
00:41:26,069 --> 00:41:27,946
into space and time, and to the aliens.

961
00:41:28,030 --> 00:41:32,367
I, Hocrates, will be rooting for you
with all my energy!

962
00:41:33,785 --> 00:41:35,996
That's right!

963
00:41:38,582 --> 00:41:41,001
If these inspire you
to create space <i>pansori</i>,

964
00:41:41,084 --> 00:41:42,586
please, don't forget

965
00:41:42,669 --> 00:41:46,965
to invite me!

966
00:41:47,925 --> 00:41:48,926
What do you think?

967
00:41:49,593 --> 00:41:50,886
I love it.

968
00:41:50,969 --> 00:41:53,555
If <i>Hodong's Bookshop</i> was <i>pansori</i>,

969
00:41:53,639 --> 00:41:54,640
how would it sound?

970
00:41:54,723 --> 00:41:56,558
<i>Hodong's Bookshop!</i>

971
00:41:56,642 --> 00:41:58,977
Today, we heard
Lee Ja-ram's tasty life story.

972
00:41:59,061 --> 00:42:01,355
That was a great read!

973
00:42:01,438 --> 00:42:05,067
WHO IS LEE JA-RAM?

974
00:42:05,150 --> 00:42:10,989
A CREATOR WHO DOESN'T LOOK FOR A PATH,

975
00:42:11,073 --> 00:42:15,077
BUT PAVES HER OWN!

976
00:42:34,388 --> 00:42:36,390
Subtitle translation by Cayle Kim
